000240introduction
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="introduction" obligation="normative">
<title>Introduction</title>
<p id="_fe58d117-8e76-4416-29ba-3068063dc13d">The publication “S-63 IHO Data Protection Scheme”, later referred to as ‘the scheme’, describes the recommended standard for the protection of ENC information. It defines security constructs and operating procedures that must be followed to ensure that the data protection scheme is operated correctly and to provide specifications that allow participants to build S-63 compliant systems and distribute data in a secure and commercially viable manner.</p>

<p id="_70b7363b-c9be-c124-73a0-c22cb9a33cfa">The Data Protection Scheme was prepared by the International Hydrographic Organisation’s (IHO) Data Protection Scheme Advisory Group (DPSWG). The S-63 standard is based on the protection scheme developed and operated by Primar and Primar-Stavanger as part of their protected ENC service. The Electronic Chart Centre AS and United Kingdom Hydrographic Office were the original contributing organisations.</p>
2

<title>Participants in the Scheme</title>
<p id="_e3e16faf-8f58-090a-2036-4046a1a2d597">There are several types of users of the scheme, these are as follows:</p>

<ul id="_31a3e39e-e513-c2c0-3551-cb9485268b7d"> <li> <p id="_1afa638a-1178-c89f-2867-e379a6c332d3">The Scheme Administrator (SA), of which there is only one.</p>

000961how_is_it_​encrypted
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="how_is_it_encrypted" obligation="normative">
<title>How is it encrypted?</title>
<p id="_429e88fb-0532-122d-81e1-c12915f4b550">Each single ENC cell file is encrypted using a unique Cell Key. The same Cell Key is used to encrypt all updates issued for the cell. The scheme however, allows for the cell keys to be incremented and changed at the discretion of the Data Server. The Cell Keys are delivered to Data Clients in the form of cell permits.</p>

<clause id="encryption_of_enc_info" obligation="normative">
2



000999the_​userpermit
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="the_userpermit" obligation="normative">
<title>The Userpermit</title>
<p id="_f352e2c8-a996-d7e0-f9f6-1e368c640bb6">The userpermit is created by OEMs and supplied to Data Clients as part of their system so that they can obtain the necessary access to encrypted ENCs from Data Servers. The following section defines the composition and format of the userpermit.</p>

<p id="_dcdaa915-f450-f31f-93a5-98e8b9555744">All Data Clients with systems capable of using data, protected with the S-63 scheme, must have a unique hardware identification (HW_ID) built into their end-user system. Such a HW_ID is often implemented as a dongle or by other means ensuring a unique identification for each installation.</p>

001070the_cell_​permit
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="the_cell_permit" obligation="normative">
<title>The Cell Permit</title>
<p id="_43cd7a68-d2bc-15d9-565a-a8bdd9db4f09">To decrypt an ENC cell the Data Client must have access to the encryption key (see <xref target="how_is_it_encrypted"/>) used to encrypt it. Since the encryption keys are only known to the Data Server there needs to be a means of delivering this information to Data Clients in a protected manner. This information is supplied by the Data Server (e.g. RENC or VAR)to the Data Client in an encrypted form known as a cell permit. A single file is provided to deliver the cell permit and is named PERMIT.TXT (see <xref target="permit_txt"/>). This file may contain several cell permits based on the ENC coverage required by the Data Client.</p>

<p id="_42e21c06-8de6-454d-aad1-255dbe2613cf">The PERMIT.TXT file will be delivered either on hard media or using online services in accordance with the Data Servers operating procedures. These procedures will be made available to Data Clients when purchasing a licence.</p>
2

001280introduction_to_​data_​authentication
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="introduction_to_data_authentication" obligation="normative">
<title>Introduction to Data Authentication and Integrity Checking</title>
<p id="_39eba2dc-5cce-1871-97ef-4246c063edc8">The digital signature technique used in the S-63 scheme uses a standard algorithm and key exchange mechanism widely used. S63 digital signatures use asymmetric public key algorithms within a PKI-like infrastructure scheme to unbreakably bind a data file with the identity of the issuer.</p>

<p id="_5fffe694-4ae2-b922-6bfa-0e8064c676be">The scheme relies on asymmetric encryption<fn reference="6"> <p id="_ea5586b3-f872-50b3-69db-b1cd4bb9ab2f">Asymmetric cryptography relies on algorithms where encryption and decryption take place with different cryptographic keys. Therefore one person can encrypt data and make available a decryption key for others to decrypt it. These keys are referred to as the “private key” and the “public key”, collectively known as a “key pair”</p>
2



001352digital_​certificates­_saa
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="digital_certificates_saa" obligation="normative">
<title>Digital Certificates (SA Authentication)</title>
<p id="_3c3e64e7-ee45-7195-4328-c2edaf58ba04">Certificates are digital files issued by a certification authority. They bind a specific public key together with other information to an individual or organisation. Certificates help prevent someone from using a fake public key to impersonate someone else. The scheme uses a chain of certificates, each one certifying the previous one until all parties are confident as to the identities in question. The SA certificate used by the IHO will be a self signed certificate<fn reference="7"> <p id="_9e333ed8-ce25-380e-8256-f2e87e49573d">The SA public key signed using the SA private key.</p>
</fn> and is the <strong>root certificate</strong> for the scheme.</p>

2



001421digital_​signatures_​vdi
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="digital_signatures_vdi" obligation="normative">
<title>Digital Signatures (Verify Data Integrity)</title>
<p id="_c6af261b-e261-3baa-a999-e1cafd5a5fd6">A digital signature is an electronic signature that can be used to authenticate the identity of the sender of a message or the signer of a document, and to ensure that the original content of the sent message is unchanged. Digital signatures are portable, easily verified and cannot be forged.</p>

<p id="_6e865557-d6f9-20ae-42e1-3617634ceda9">It is also acceptable for Hydrographic offices or other Data Server organisations (e.g. RENC/VAR) to use digital signatures to maintain provenance and data integrity between them in the delivery of ENC information. Each ENC file (both base and update files) will always have a single unique signature file associated with it. No other files in an encrypted ENC exchange set have a digital signature.<note id="_a3315633-fd45-a9c8-64d6-8e4a43599af6"> <p id="_b87f0ea4-0938-18e1-23bd-e329dea0e737">An exchange set may contain signatures issued by different data servers and therefore each ENC file must be authenticated individually.</p>
2

<title>Data Authentication File Formats</title>
<p id="_3aa9f6eb-0b0a-cd93-4ef7-dcc5db32cffa">There are a number of files associated with the authentication processes within the S-63 Data Protection Scheme. Although these may be derived independently the various component parts contained within each file share common elements that are always formatted in the same way. 001709enc_​product_listing
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="enc_product_listing" obligation="normative">
<title>ENC Product Listing (PRODUCTS.TXT)</title>
<p id="_12958a2f-09a7-d5b1-1974-7558cb8a7ebc">The file named ‘PRODUCTS.TXT’ will be supplied with each encrypted exchange set and will be stored in a folder named ‘INFO’ held in root directory. It is the mechanism for managing data within an ENC Service and exchanging it with data already held in the Data Client’s system SENC. The structure and format of this file is described in more detail in <xref target="product_list_file_structure"/>, <xref target="product_list_header"/>, <xref target="product_list_enc_section"/> &amp; <xref target="product_list_ecs_section"/>.</p>

<p id="_33e3b6dd-6aa5-a774-f805-33490a2936ca">There are two types of PRODUCTS.TXT file, “PARTIAL” and “FULL”. A partial products listing contains the current status of all ENCs contained in a single exchange set. A full product listing contains the current status of ALL cells in a Data Server’s service, that is, all exchange sets. Although procedures may vary between Data Servers a full product listing will always be provided with the weekly update exchange set. In instances where a Data Server issues a complete set of new base media (no weekly update), each base media must contain a full product list of all ENCs in a service<note id="_49aeffe4-7e5a-034e-fb51-e74c55d13205"> <p id="_dcf441e8-7ce9-24c0-bef0-e6ccd4086ad5">OEMs should ensure that their systems are able to handle “FULL” and “PARTIAL” product listings (<xref target="product_list_header"/> refers). Base CDs may contain a partial listing with only the contents of the CD included. The Update will always carry a full product listing of all available ENCs in a Data Server’s Service.</p>

<clause id="product_list_enc_section" obligation="normative">
<title>Product List ‘ENC’ Section</title>

002064the_s57_​catalogue_​file
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="the_s57_catalogue_file" obligation="normative">
<title>The S-57 Catalogue File (CATALOG.031)</title>
<p id="_9920e145-505a-893c-f379-dfb29f0855f9">The “Data Set Identification” [DSID] field is used by ECS/ECDIS to ensure that base cells and update files are imported to the SENC in the correct sequence and without omission. Since the complete ENC Cell file is encrypted, information in the DSID field of each cell file is not available to OEM systems, unless it is decrypted first.</p>

<p id="_9793564a-04db-7408-ab56-cc19e11bef5f">The “Comments” [CATD-COMT] field in each cell record of the CATALOG.031 file is used to store the required DSID information. Since the CATALOG.031 file acts as the table of contents for the exchange set and identifies where all files are stored it is ideally suited for this purpose.</p>
2

002150the_catd_​comt_​structure_and_​format
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="the_catd_comt_structure_and_format" obligation="normative">
<title>The CATD-COMT Structure and Format</title>
<p id="_a88b19e1-4369-e57e-ee3a-93cc07185f8c">The DSID information stored in the CATD-COMT field is subdivided into four or five comma separated subfields. This is dependant on whether the ENC file has an EN or ER application profile. The final subfield is punctuated by a semi colon (;).</p>

<example id="_3a1d38cc-36a9-1084-a5cd-0549cf91bc4a" unnumbered="true"> <p id="_1b37282b-273e-8e85-d564-8ff9bb28c0c3"> <tt>VERSION=1.0,EDTN=1,UPDN=0,UADT=20060703,ISDT=20060703;</tt> <br/> <tt>VERSION=1.0,EDTN=1,UPDN=1,ISDT=20060710;</tt> </p>

002221enc_​update_​management
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="enc_update_management" obligation="normative">
<title>ENC Update Management</title>
<p id="_7ee95ff9-00d7-02bb-3f54-f0ea3c59c251">A file is supplied that allows Data Clients to check the compatibility and suitability of a particular ENC update exchange set prior to import. The Data Client can use this file to check that the last Base Exchange sets imported to the SENC are compatible with the update currently being installed on the ECDIS. This file describes the current status of all base media associated with a data server’s service. It is named STATUS.LST. The following section describes the format and content in more detail.</p>

<clause id="status_lst_file" obligation="normative">
2



002225status_​lst_file
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="status_lst_file" obligation="normative">
<title>STATUS.LST File</title>
<p id="_f3294851-e7ae-6578-06be-f3779d136852">This file will be stored in the INFO folder on the Update Exchange Media that relates to base media containing either a single media set or multiple ones (see <xref target="appendix2"/>). It is supplied so that Data Clients can check the current status of the SENC against available base media. This file can be used to check that an update exchange set is compatible with the latest base media installed on the Data Client. An update media MUST be made available at regular intervals<fn reference="9"> <p id="_5831ad1e-1687-7f9c-d87b-605f42a48cca">Even if all bases are re-issued in the same week, although this is considered unlikely.</p>
</fn> for services provided in accordance with this version of the standard.<note id="_db75154b-aa99-9010-2cc4-974bcc295fde"> <p id="_f88b802b-1e6b-bf1d-4377-2459f05bb69a">When the data server issues a new update only one update media will be supplied. However there may be more than one update exchange set on a single update media in the case of services supplied on large media such as DVD.</p>
</note> </p>

002411cd_rom
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="cd_rom" obligation="normative">
<title>CD-ROM</title>
<p id="_1c9d74c2-c99e-a4dd-07ce-fb6b10aa9d6b">Encrypted exchange sets delivered by this method will be given the volume ID consistent with the IHO S-57 Data Protection Scheme, i.e. V01X03, V01X02, etc. S-63 can be delivered as a single exchange set across multiple CD-ROMs but experience gained by existing Data Servers has shown this to be inadvisable. The method currently operated by certain Data Servers is to issue single exchanges sets across multiple CDs.</p>

002453create_​top_level_​key_pair
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="create_top_level_key_pair" obligation="normative">
<title>Create Top Level Key Pair</title>
<p id="_7659584b-91d2-69fa-d135-4f5dafe81bd2">The IHO as scheme administrator must create a top level public and private key pair. The private key will be used to sign Data Server certificates and the public key to authenticate the signature. The public key must be installed on the Data Clients system independently of the Encrypted ENC data.</p>

<clause id="create_pqg_parameters" obligation="normative">
2



002481create_​and_issue_sa_​digital_​certificate
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="create_and_issue_sa_digital_certificate" obligation="normative">
<title>Create and Issue SA Digital Certificate (X509v3)</title>
<p id="_7a06c88f-ae35-3459-bf16-74d094926344">The SA Digital Certificate will be compliant with X509v3 <eref type="inline" bibitemid="ITU-T_X.509" citeas="ITU-T X.509 (11/1988)"/>. The SA Digital Certificate will always be provided in a file called IHO.CRT. The IHO.CRT file is available from IHO at <link target="https://iho.int/">www.iho.int</link>.</p>

<p id="_9e43635d-a9c5-a99c-2d59-cf15476e1423">The SA uses a DSA Public Key of length 512 bits.</p>
2



002517process_​applications­_from_​data_servers_​oems
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="process_applications_from_data_servers_oems" obligation="normative">
<title>Process Applications from Data Servers &amp; OEMs</title>
<p id="_508209ff-988a-02fd-67af-150566584878">The Scheme Administrator is responsible for processing applications from Data Servers and OEMs who wish to subscribe to the IHO S-63 ENC Data Protection Scheme. This includes the management and issuing SA Signed certificates to Data Servers and the management and issuing of Manufacturer Codes (M_ID &amp; M_KEY) to accepted OEMs and their distribution to authorised Data Servers. The application processes are outlined in more detail at <strong>ANNEX A</strong> &amp; <strong>ANNEX B</strong> of this document.</p>

<clause id="process_data_server_request_for_data_server_certficate" obligation="normative">
2



002521process_​data_server_​request_​for_data_​server_​certficate

<title>Process Data Server Request for Data Server Certificate</title>
<p id="_c3ba6878-ec3e-6092-857a-1800e0968748">A successful Data Server applicant will be required to supply a certificate signed with the Data Server private key, this is known as Self Signed Key (SSK). The certification process is then carried out by the SA and is detailed step by step below.</p>

<title>Process OEM Application</title>
<p id="_6e4ae60b-05d0-6190-ea80-75088bbec778">Manufacturers must apply to the SA to become a member of the IHO S-63 Data Protection Scheme.</p>

2



002682produce_​public_​private_key_​pair
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="produce_public_private_key_pair" obligation="normative">
<title>Produce Public/Private Key Pair</title>
<p id="_e4e83471-f95e-1c2d-22c7-ad2c32f35899">Data Servers will need to create a Private and Public Key pair as part of the ‘asymmetric’ encryption methodology adopted by the IHO S-63 Data Protection Scheme. The Data Server’s Public and Private Keys are used in the following functions:</p>

<ul id="_87e2f0e3-ed2e-eca3-fa91-e2ce10c7403e"> <li> <p id="_86487666-ba87-00bb-9f85-2871e20725e8">The Private Key is used to sign the Data Server’s Public Key to create a Self Signed Certificate (SSK).</p>
2



002722create_​data_server_​ssk
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="create_data_server_ssk" obligation="normative">
<title>Create Data Server Self Signed Key (SSK)</title>
<p id="_3bea860e-c87a-5bc4-7600-3e3e72f40d50">The SSK is created and submitted to the SA to obtain a Data Server Certificate. The SSK contains the Data Server public key with a signature created by the Data Server. Although the SSK format is identical to the Data Server Certificate defined in <xref target="create_data_server_certificate"/>, the only difference is the SSK is created by the Data Server and the Data Server Certificate which is created and issued by the SA.</p>

<p id="_95e48efe-35d1-d8d9-3d50-a7f90e1247fe">The SSK defines a signature of the Data Server’s public key. The input to the signature should be the Data Server’s public key, formatted according to the Public Key file format as described in <xref target="the_y_format"/>. The SSK file shall be written as ASCII text with the format, structure and order described in <xref target="the_ssk_format"/>.</p>

<clause id="management_of_eck" obligation="normative">
<title>Management of Encryption Cell Keys (ECK)</title>
<p id="_96c7a8ba-dd16-0a95-8661-be2f5027697f">Each ENC is encrypted using a unique cell key and each ENC permit has the capability to store two encrypted cell keys. These keys may be incremented from time to time at the discretion of the Data Server therefore it is important to manage them in an efficient and effective manner.</p>

<p id="_ee7d573d-9d90-cfd7-14cf-0c04623902e3">To create new cell keys and increment existing ones the Data Server will require an application to automatically manage the keys and store them securely. This application must have a method of generating random strings of the correct length and ideally a means of checking that duplicate cell keys are not produced within a set.</p>

003254enc_cell_​permit_​installation

<clause id="enc_cell_permit_installation" obligation="normative">
<title>ENC Cell Permit Installation</title>
<p id="_ee23ac3f-e2a9-9e08-9a47-5741b2d80be0">New Cell permits are delivered to a Data Client’s system in a file named PERMIT.TXT. The structure and format of this file are given in <xref target="the_cell_permit"/>. The Data Clients system must be able to read in this file and perform a number of checks. Each cell permit record contains a Data Server ID that enables OEMs to manage permits and data in a multi supplier environment. The following sections outline how this file must be managed and the checks that must be carried out when installing a new permit file.</p>

<title>ENC Authentication and Integrity Checks</title>
<p id="_585304fa-ac20-3146-204b-322ce3ca5154">OEM systems must be capable of authenticating the source of the encrypted ENC data and validate its integrity. This is achieved in two ways as follows:</p>

<ul id="_e4ddd6c7-7b79-16b2-6622-0829b0e0d2fd"> <li> <p id="_5ccd8fc0-7397-242a-8da0-c5616d5f6685">By Authenticating the SA signature held as part of the Data Server Certificate that forms part of the ENC signature file.</p>
2



003395authenticate_verify_​sa_​digital_​certificate
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="authenticate_verify_sa_digital_certificate" obligation="normative">
<title>Authenticate/Verify SA Digital Certificate</title>
<p id="_41fbcabc-b6ad-4ae6-c240-943f055bbee3">This procedure is performed by OEMs or Data Clients to verify that the SA public key installed on the ECS/ECDIS is correct and current in respect of the IHO S-63 Data Protection Scheme. It is this SA public key that is used to authenticate the SA signed Data Server Certificate supplied by Data Servers as part of the ENC signature file. The procedure is as follows:</p>

<p id="_07a32451-c7e9-be9d-cf15-c1103f87d6fd">Manually compare the SA public key contained within the independently installed SA Digital Certificate with a copy of the printable public key available from the IHO website (<link target="https://iho.int/">www.iho.int</link>). If the above check fails, the system shall not accept the SA Digital Certificate. Otherwise, the SA Digital Certificate is valid and the Data Server public key it contains can be used to authenticate SA signed Data Server Certificate held as part of the ENC signature file.<note id="_8dd9f7af-3761-2fbe-14b2-3db9dae3bfe2"> <p id="_00f30009-73ce-b1ca-528a-ff097fa88dfb">The Data Client must have means by which users can access the installed certificate from the application.</p>
2



003454authenticate_sa_​signed_data_​server_​certificate_10
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="authenticate_sa_signed_data_server_certificate_10" obligation="normative">
<title>Authenticate SA signed Data Server Certificate</title>
<p id="_ba597c88-b96d-f76e-5532-19409d067c81">This procedure is performed by the Data Client’s system to authenticate the SA signed Data Server Certificate stored as part of the ENC signature file against the installed SA public key. This process is carried out before the Data Server public key is extracted to authenticate the ENC signature. Refer to <xref target="enc_signature_file_naming_convention"/> for the structure of signature/certificate pairs in a signature file.</p>

<p id="_753e6248-e464-c8a7-fb98-2b617a4c2545">Prior to the authentication process the system must first check the availability, format and status of the certificate or public key installed on the system. If there are any problems this should be reported to the data client in a meaningful way as follows:</p>

003668data_​client_​permanent_​warnings
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="data_client_permanent_warnings" obligation="normative">
<title>Data Client Permanent Warnings</title>
<p id="_e78de570-d028-7103-3ffd-7079eea2d8a4">The data client already carries out checks when loading ENC permits and data files to validate conformance with this standard. However any resultant errors or warnings messages are not always translated through to the ECDIS when it is in use, e.g. route planning or navigation. It is possible, under the current data protection scheme, to use ENCs that are out-of-date without the user being aware of it. The purpose of this section is to identify any messages that should be permanently displayed by the data client when in use.</p>

<p id="_e0e6dc02-3256-f726-1fe4-498ce2fbad79">The data client must display permanent warning messages in the viewer when it can be determined that ENC information contained in the SENC is or may be out-of-date. The data client must carry out the following checks when displaying a cell in the ECDIS:</p>

<title>Conditions of Use for the Test data</title>
<p id="_8ce0be8c-aa44-dd84-e3cd-1b51c27b45bb">The ENC information (the material) included in the test data has been made available to the recipient solely for the purpose of testing their application and verifying compliance with the S-63 standard. The material is supplied under the conditions shown below. If the recipient does not agree to be bound by these conditions then the material should not be used and it should be destroyed.</p>

<title>Media Overview</title>
<p id="_fdb67856-a294-144a-e645-393914bdf2b7">The following section gives a high level view of how the data will be structured on the media. Detailed information relating to the content and format of these folders and files are provided later in this appendix.</p>

005267_media_​folder_and_​file_​structure
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_media_folder_and_file_structure" obligation="informative">
<title>Media Folder and File Structure</title>
<p id="_da74b79c-f4a8-7ec4-10aa-3b6d5adb7488">All exchange sets are located in the root directory of each media each within their own specific sub-directory. The configuration of all exchange sets are the same as outlined in 7.5.1 of the main document with the one notable exception. The <strong> <em>“INFO”</em> </strong> folder that includes the <strong> <em>“PRODUCTS.TXT”</em> </strong> file will no longer be stored in the root directory of the exchange set(s) but in the root directory of the media.</p>

<p id="_ef75210c-048b-e3b6-b2cb-a03d11527257">The <strong> <em>“INFO”</em> </strong> will continue to be used by data servers to include additional files unique and specific to their S-63 encrypted ENC services. Note that any data server specific files stored in this folder must be named in such a way that they <strong>DO NOT</strong> conflict with the S-63 file naming convention.</p>
2



005279_media_​identificatio­n
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_media_identification" obligation="informative">
<title>Media Identification</title>
<p id="_54da1395-39e4-09f3-223b-a9bd7bf093b5">There must be a method for differentiating between services provided on CD and those supplied using large media support. The first differentiator is the volume ID of the media (see <xref target="media_labelling"/>). This will identify the use of large media format and notify the data client of the expected folder and file structure.</p>

<p id="_9a06a427-5886-f046-4844-f39e2ccbecc4">A further indication is the presence of the new MEDIA.TXT file is in the root directory of the media is a further indication that an ENC service is being provided using large media support.</p>
2



005310_media_​listing_​media_txt
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_media_listing_media_txt" obligation="informative">
<title>Media Listing (MEDIA.TXT)</title>
<p id="_a214e97c-66a1-a0fb-9bef-2f016b28bcc8">This is a new file designed to manage services supplied using large media support. It is located in the root directory of the base and update media and contains information relating to all media in a data server’s service and the exchange sets contained on the media. The main purpose of this file is as follows:</p>

<ul id="_714a6256-e096-6af0-9f69-d72546e2f004"> <li> <p id="_4ce71783-12d2-57c5-c2cf-abda61d8aa35">To provide data clients with a means to manage the import of a data server’s service that supports large media.</p>
2

005487_media_​management_​data_​clients
Hanging paragraph in clause
<clause id="_media_management_data_clients" obligation="informative">
<title>Media Management (Data Clients)</title>
<p id="_c753cded-19b3-929f-c7e5-bd0bb4d00c4f">As the volume of ENCs continues to grow a more intelligent and “smarter” method of loading them into ECDIS/ECS is required. Since most customer only purchase a subset of all available ENCs it would seem prudent to base the import of S-63 encrypted ENCs directly against the customers permit holdings. The following bullet points are provided to illustrate the recommended steps for importing encrypted ENCs.</p>
